he focus of planned analyses will be on infants? early social-cognitive abilities. Increasing evidence exists of early emerging social-cognitive abilities, such as the ability to monitor others? attention and the ability to imitate others. Building up on data already collected or&amp;nbsp; that are being collected, it is intended to contribute to the study of the developmental role of early social competencies and the role of individual differences and parental styles.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Firstly, data collected during the fellow?s PhD suggest that after the second month of age, infants demonstrate interrelated social attention skills, namely abilities to engage in activities jointly with parents or adults. It is planned to further investigate how parents manage to involve infants? attention at this early age and how infants? individual differences relate to differences in interactive styles displayed by parents across the first months of life.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Secondly, using observational data that are being collected as part of the Cardiff Child Development Study, the relations between individual differences in infants? social attention, parental styles and imitative skills in 6-month-olds will be investigated. This study will contribute to the understanding of the bases of imitation, which is an important skill because it allows learning of problem-solving methods from others.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-06-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>29204</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>5B9670A1-AD03-464C-9A76-824FBDC6B14F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Reducing the mapping between perception and action facilitates imitation</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>British Journal of Developmental Psychology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/9eaa3d1a5280d5824d58ceb959c709d0"><gtr:id>9eaa3d1a5280d5824d58ceb959c709d0</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Perra O</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfbdfbdc1cbc2b</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>97DFCB7B-A516-49D3-A135-41A97091F72C</gtr:id><gtr:title>Imitation and 'theory of mind' competencies in discrimination of autism from other neur